{{Use British English|date=July 2013}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}
[[File:SeychellesBIOT1970.jpg|280px|thumb|The British Indian Ocean Territory prior to the [[Seychelles]]' independence in 1976. The land at bottom left is the northern tip of [[Madagascar]]. ([[Desroches Island|Desroches]] is not labelled, but is a part of the [[Amirante Islands]].)]]
[[File:Biot-map.png|thumb|280px|Map of the British Indian Ocean Territory since 1976.]]
The [[British Indian Ocean Territory]] (BIOT) is an archipelago of 55 islands in the [[Indian Ocean]] South of [[India]], it is situated approximately halfway between Africa and [[Indonesia]]. The islands form a semicircular group with an open sea towards the east. The largest, [[Diego Garcia]], is located at the southern extreme end. It measures {{convert|60|km2}} and accounts for almost three-quarters of the total land area of the territory.{{sfn|Notholt|2008|p=5}}{{Disputed inline|Land area of Deigo Garcia and Notholt 2008, p. 5.|reason=According to other sources, 60 square kilometres is the total land area of the territory, and the land area of Diego Garcia is around 30 square kilometres.|date=August 2017}} Diego Garcia is the only inhabited island and is home to the joint UK-US [[Camp Justice (Diego Garcia)|naval support facility]].<ref name=World/><ref name=britannica>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/80241/British-Indian-Ocean-Territory|title=British Indian Ocean Territory|accessdate=23 June 2013|work=Encyclopædia Britannica}}</ref> Other islands within the archipelago include [[Danger Island, Great Chagos Bank|Danger Island]], [[Three Brothers, Chagos|Three Brothers]] Islands, [[Nelsons Island|Nelson Island]], and [[Peros Banhos]], as well as the island groups of the [[Egmont Islands]], [[Eagle Islands]], and the [[Salomon Islands]].<ref name=britannica/>

==Physical geography==
BIOT is an archipelago of 55 islands.{{sfn|Central Intelligence Agency|2010|p=93}} They were annexed by the UK in 1965 under the Treaty of Paris from a much larger archipelago which in 1804 consisted of 2,300 independent islands.<ref name=World>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/asia/biot.htm|title=British Indian Ocean Territory|accessdate=23 June 2013|publisher=WorldAtlas.com}}</ref><ref name=britannica/> BIOT is situated in the Indian Ocean near the [[Equator]]. It is roughly halfway between Africa and [[Indonesia]], about {{convert|1000|miles}} southwest of India.<ref name=World/>{{sfn|Central Intelligence Agency|2010|p=93}} It is situated approximately {{convert|1600|km}} from [[South India]] and {{convert|600|km}} to the south of the [[Maldives]]{{sfn|Haggett|2001|p=2627}} With a [[coastline]] stretching {{convert|698|km}}, it is the southern extension of the [[Chagos-Laccadive Ridge]].{{sfn|Green|2006|p=408}} The [[Chagos Islands]] archipelago are northeast of [[Mauritius]], while [[Agalega Islands]] are due north.{{sfn|Paul|1987|p=146}} The islands are characterised as [[coral atoll]]s whose formation occurred at the summits of volcanic mountains these being submerged. The terrain is flat and low, with most areas not exceeding {{convert|2|m}} above sea level.{{sfn|Central Intelligence Agency|2010|p=93}}

The climate is tropical marine; hot, humid, and moderated by trade winds. It is located outside the route of the cyclones.<ref name=britannica/>

===Marine reserve===
{{main|Chagos Marine Protected Area}}
[[File:Ctenella.jpg|left|thumbnail|''[[Ctenella]]'']]
The lagoon that surrounds the atoll has an area of about {{convert|120|km2|sqmi}}. The maximum water depth in the lagoon is about {{convert|25|m|ft}}. The width of the coral reef varies from {{convert|100|-|200|m|ft}} with a shallow depth of about {{convert|1|m|ft}} on the seaward side. The area covered by the fringing seaward reef shelf is about {{convert|35.2|km2|sqmi}}. The bed slope noted at the outer edge of the reef shelf is steep towards the deeper end; the depth drops to more than {{convert|450|m|ft}} in some areas within {{convert|1|km|mi}} distance from the shore.

In 2010, the whole territory, as well as {{convert|545000|km2|sqmi|0}} of ocean around the islands, was declared a [[marine reserve]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Blue Reef visitors win support for the Chago campaign|publisher=[[BBC]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/cornwall/hi/people_and_places/nature/newsid_8605000/8605317.stm|accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref> It is known formally as the [[Chagos Marine Protected Area]],<ref name=marine-conservation.org.uk>{{cite web|title=Chagos Island Marine Reserve |url=http://www.marine-conservation.org.uk/chagos.html |publisher=Marine Conservation Society (UK) SouthEast |accessdate=23 June 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321094648/http://www.marine-conservation.org.uk/chagos.html |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> because it is a "pristine ocean ecosystem now representing 16% of the world's fully protected coral reef."{{sfn|Acton|2012|p=524}} Fishing is banned within the reserve area.<ref name=britannica /> Diego Garcia is a [[List of Ramsar sites in British Overseas Territories|Ramsar site]].<ref name=ramsar.org2001>{{cite web |title=Diego García inscrito en la Lista de Ramsar / Diego Garcia, atoll de l'océan Indian, inscrit sur la liste de Ramsar |url=http://www.ramsar.org/cda/en/ramsar-documents-list-diego-garcia-inscrito-en/main/ramsar/1-31-218%5E16549_4000_0__ |publisher=Ramsar |accessdate=1 July 2013 |language=Spanish |date=8 October 2001 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707091407/http://www.ramsar.org/cda/en/ramsar-documents-list-diego-garcia-inscrito-en/main/ramsar/1-31-218%5E16549_4000_0__ |archivedate=7 July 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>

===Landforms===
Of the 55 islands of the [[Chagos Archipelago]], [[Diego Garcia]] is the largest. Aside from this, the main islands are the Egmont Islands, Danger Island, Aigle (Eagle) Islands, Three Brothers, Nelson Island, Salomon Islands, and Peros Banhos at the northern end of the Chagos Archipelago.{{sfn|Vine|2011|p=22}}7478

===Diego Garcia===
{{Double image|right|Diegogarcia.jpg|200|The O Club on Diego Garcia.jpg|240|Left: [[Diego Garcia]]. Right: All of the unpaved roads present on the Diego Garcia island are made of white crushed coral.}}
The coral atoll of Diego Garcia is approximately {{convert|1970|nmi|km}} east of the coast of Africa (at [[Tanzania]]), {{convert|967|nmi|km}} south-southwest of the southern tip of India (at [[Kanyakumari]]) and {{convert|2550|nmi|km}} west-northwest of the west coast of Australia (at [[Cape Range National Park]], Western Australia). Diego Garcia lies at the southernmost tip of the [[Chagos-Laccadive Ridge]]&nbsp;—&#32;a vast submarine range in the Indian Ocean.<ref>{{NatGeo ecoregion|id=im0125|name=Maldives-Lakshadweep-Chagos Archipelago tropical moist forests}}</ref> The total area encompassed by the atoll is {{convert|169.6|km2|sqmi}}. At the entrance to the lagoon, there are three small islands, and these are East Island ({{convert|7.49|ha}}), Middle Island ({{convert|4.98|ha}}), and West Island ({{convert|2|ha}}).<ref>[[#NRMP|Natural Resources Management Plan (2005)]], paragraph 2.5.1.</ref> In some areas, the atoll has both marshes and wetlands.<ref>[[#NRMP|Natural Resources Management Plan (2005)]], paragraph 3.3.2.1.</ref> The ecosystem consists of undisturbed tropical forests.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mauritius stakes claim for Chagos|date=30 March 2004|publisher=[[BBC]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/3583927.stm|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref>

===Peros Benhos Atoll===
The [[Peros Banhos]] Islands, which are the largest group on the Chagos Bank, consists of 27 islands scattered around the rim of an immense lagoon, which has a perimeter of {{convert|12|league|km}} and enclosed some 310 square km of water.  They consist of several groups of islets and reefs; deep channels separate them.{{sfn|Tuckey|1815|pp=64-65}} They had a population of some 400 islanders before the evacuation in 1965, the largest number living on '''Île du Coin''' in the southwest corner of the atoll (in the previous century, the dominant island was '''Île Diamant''' in the northwest corner of the atoll); in all, there were seven inhabited islands.

===Salomon Atoll===
[[File:Boddam2.jpg|thumbnail|left| Île Boddam, with Île Diable in the background.]]
Some 25&nbsp;km east of Peros Panhos Atoll, the smaller [[Salomon Islands|Salomon group]] comprises eleven islands clustered around a lagoon measuring 8&nbsp;km long and 5&nbsp;km wide. Prior to the removal of its population, six of the islands were inhabited with a total of about 250 islanders. '''Île Boddam''' in the southwest was the principal settlement, while '''Île Takamaka''' in the east wasc the centre of boatbuilding for the archipelago.

===Nelson Island, Three Brother Islands and Eagle Islands===
Lying between Diego Garcia in the south, and the Peros Banhos and Salomon Atolls in the north, the remaining coralline islands are scattered over a wide area of the Great Chagos Bank, an area of atolls, reefs and shoals with an average depth of water of some 20 metres. Uninhabited [[Nelsons Island|'''Île Nelson''']] lies 35&nbsp;km south of Salomon Atoll. A hundred km to the southwest of Nelson are the 3 islands of [[Three Brothers, Chagos|'''Trois Frères''']], which were briefly inhabited in the 19th century. Further west lies the [[Eagle Islands|'''Île d'Aigle''']], which was inhabited until 1935. [[Île Vache Marine]], the southernmost of the [[Eagle Islands]], lies south.<ref>[[British Admiralty]] [[nautical chart]] 11000030 – 3 Chagos Archipelago, Scale 1:360,000</ref>

===Danger Island===
[[Danger Island, Great Chagos Bank|'''Île Danger''']], 20&nbsp;km south of Île d'Aigle, has never been inhabited; it is a {{convert|2|km}} long and flat island with a maximum width of {{convert|400|m|ft}}. It is covered with tall [[coconut tree]]s and shrubs.

===Six Îles, or Egmont Atoll===
Finally, [[Egmont Islands|'''Six Îles''' Atoll]] (also called '''Egmont'''), {{convert|5|league|km}} further south of Danger, was also occupied for short periods during the mid 19th century{{sfn|Evers|Kooy|2011|p=27}}  until 1935. Besides the six named islands, the atoll also includes a seventh unnamed island. The atoll, in the form of “U”, is a small strip of land with width varying from {{convert|30|m|ft}} to a maximum of {{convert|3|km|mi}} at its northern extremity. The total land area of the atoll is {{convert|2430|ha}}. A fringing reef circumscribes the atoll. There are two openings into the ocean. It almost encompasses a large lagoon. The lagoon itself is {{convert|20|km|mi}} in length and is more than {{convert|10|km|mi}} in width. Rounded pumic stones found on the eastern beach of the island by one of the explorers of the island have been inferred as debris from the [[Krakatoa]] volcanic eruption of 1883 {{sfn|Paul|1987|p=14}} The atoll is {{convert|23|league|km}} to the northwest of Diego Garcia, on the Great Chagos Bank. The islands are connected by reefs which are steep and there are no locations for anchorage on its shores.{{sfn|Tuckey|1815|pp=64-65}}

==Human geography==
[[File:BIOT geodesic survey.jpg|thumbnail|US personnel bringing survey equipment onto Diego Garcia, helped by [[Chagossians|Ilois]], 1971.]]
{{main|Depopulation of Chagossians from the Chagos Archipelago}}
In the late 18th century, coconut palm plantations were established on the island to produce [[copra]] for which slave labourers were brought in from Africa.<ref name=britannica />{{sfn|Haggett|2001|p=2627}} A small population lived in the archipelago, descendents of Mauritian laborers working the copra industry.{{sfn|Dupont|2001|p=1120}} After an agreement was signed in 1966 between Britain and the United States, the US built a [[Camp Justice (Diego Garcia)|military base]] and forcibly evacuated all indigenous people; 1,200 from Diego Garcia, Ile du Coin, and Île Boddam were relocated to Mauritius,{{sfn|Olson|Shadle|1991|p=90}} while others went to the Seychelles. In 2000, the Chagos islanders won an appeal which restored their authority to live on the islands, and they received UK citizenship in the following year.<ref name=britannica /> A 2008 court decision blocked their return. Further complications arose after the 2010 establishment of the world's largest marine reserve as the islanders' commercial fishing capabilities, if they returned to the archipelago, would be curtailed, thus hampering their traditional livelihood.{{sfn|Russell|2012|p=269}}

