{{Infobox Disputed Islands | plural = | name = Namyit Island | image name = | pushpin map = South China Sea | native name = | archipelago = [[Spratly Islands]] | native name link = | other_names = | location = [[South China Sea]] | coordinates = {{coord|10|10|54|N|114|21|36|E|display=inline,title}} | country claim = China | country 1 claim = Philippines | country 2 claim = Taiwan | country = Vietnam | country admin divisions title = | country admin divisions = }} {{Annotated image | float=right | caption = NASA's satellite photo of Namyit Island | image = Tizard Bank, Spratly Islands.png | width = 250 | image-width = 1700 | height = 200 | image-top = -720 | image-left = -390 | annotations = | image caption = | image size = }} '''Namyit Island''' ({{lang-vi|Đảo Nam Yết}}; {{zh|s=鸿庥岛|t=鴻庥島|p=Hongxiu Dao}}; {{lang-tl|Binago}}) is the third-largest island on [[Tizard Bank]] in the northwest of the [[Spratly Islands]] in [[South China Sea]]. With an area of {{convert|5.3|ha}}, it is the [[List of Spratly Islands by area|twelfth-largest]] naturally-occurring Spratly island, and the fifth-largest among the [[Vietnam|Vietnamese]]-occupied islands. The island is also claimed by [[China]], the [[Philippines]] and [[Taiwan]].
==History in the 20th century== Although two [[South Vietnam]]ese warships (the HQ-04 ''Tuy Dong'' and HQ-05 ''Tay Ket'') stopped at Namyit Island in 1962,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nghiencuubiendong.vn/download/doc_download/131-white-paper-on-the-hoang-sa-paracel-and-truong-sa-spratly-islands-part-2 |title=White Paper on the Hoang Sa (Paracel) and Truong Sa (Spratly) Islands (1975) [part 2, split by uploading site] |publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Republic of Vietnam) |accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> South Vietnamese troops did not set up a permanent garrison on the islet until August 1973. On 6 September 1973, the [[South Vietnam|Republic of Vietnam]]'s Ministry of the Interior signed Decree No. 420-BNV/HCĐP/26 merging some Spratly islands, including Namyit, into Phuoc Hai Commune, Dat Do District, [[Phuoc Tuy Province]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vietnam.vn/a-number-historical-and-uridical-documents-on-vietnams-sovereignty-over-the-truong-sa-and-hoang-sa-archipelagoespart-3-c1070n20111021084743296.htm |title=A number historical and juridical documents on Vietnam’s sovereignty over the Truong Sa and Hoang Sa archipelagoes- Part 3 |publisher=Authority of Foreign Information Service, Ministry of Information and Communications (Vietnam) |date=21 October 2011 |accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> South Vietnam continued to administer the entity until 27 April 1975 when their troops were evicted by the [[Vietnam People's Army]].{{fact|date=July 2015}}
==Geography== {{convert|11|nmi|km|abbr=off}} to the south of Itu Aba Island,<ref name="vnnavy">{{vi}} {{cite book |title=Những điều cần biết về hai quần đảo Hoàng Sa, Trường Sa và khu vực thềm lục địa phía nam [What you need to know about Paracel Islands, Spratly Islands and southern continental shelf] |year=2011 |publisher=Political Department, Naval Command (Vietnam)}}</ref> Namyit Island is a small oval-shaped [[coral island]] which is {{convert|600|m|yd|abbr=off}} long and {{convert|125|m|yd|abbr=off}} wide. The [[coral reef]]<!--can it be called "fringing reef"?--> on which the island lies is {{convert|0.2|m|ftin|abbr=off}} to {{convert|0.4|m|ftin|abbr=off}} above the sea during [[low tide]].<ref name="vnnavy" /> There is a [[heliport]] at the end of island.<ref name="Gazetter">{{cite web | title = Digital Gazetter of Spratly Islands | url = http://www.southchinasea.org/macand/gazetteer.htm | accessdate = 22 March 2008 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100827072842/http://southchinasea.org/macand/gazetteer.htm | archivedate = 27 August 2010 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>
Namyit Island Light is a white round tower with red bands standing {{convert|23|m|ft|abbr=off}} in height.
==Ecology== Namyit Island has no source of [[fresh water]], and its [[coral sand]] is not suitable for plants in general. The island is covered with small trees, bushes and grass and is inhabited by sea birds.<ref name="Gazetter" /> The surrounding water is home to 492 species of [[plankton]], 86 species of [[seaweed]], two species of [[seagrass]], 225 species of [[Benthos|benthic organisms]], 160 species of [[coral]], 414 species of [[reef fish]] and two species of [[sea turtle]]s.<ref name="tp">{{vi}} {{cite news |title=Lập Khu bảo tồn biển Nam Yết |author=Nguyễn Đình Quân |url=http://www.tienphong.vn/ban-doc/591660/Lap-Khu-bao-ton-bien-Nam-Yet-tpp.html |publisher=Tiền phong online |date=15 September 2012 |accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Truong Sa District]] *[[Spratly Islands dispute]]
